new history, Workers on Arrival, Joe William Trotter, Jr. refutes these perceptions by charting the black working class's vast contributions to the making of America. Covering the last four hundred years since Africans were first brought to Virginia in 1619, Trotter traces black workers' complicated journey from the transatlantic slave trade through the American Century to the demise of the industrial order in the 21st century. At the center of this compelling, fast-paced narrative are the actual experiences of these African American men and women. A dynamic and vital history of remarkable contributions despite repeated setbacks, Workers on Arrival expands our understanding of America's economic and industrial growth, its cities, ideas, and institutions, and the real challenges confronting black urban communities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxEmploymentxHistory. 0aWorking class African AmericansxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1619.  aafrican american culture.  aafricans.  aamerican century.  aassets.  ablack lives matter.  ablack poor.  ablack urban communities.  ablack working class.  aconsumers.  adynamic history.  aeconomic growth.  aemployment.  ahealth.  ahousing.  aindustrial growth.  aindustrial order.  alethal police community relations.  aliabilities.  amaking of america.  anew history.  aperceptions.  apoverty.  aproducers.  aracial conflict.  asocial conflict.  atransatlantic slave trade.  avirginia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz97831106101